Heat a drizzle of oil in a large #frying pan{} on medium-high heat.

Once hot, add the @breadcrumbs{25%g}. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{} and fry, stirring regularly, until lightly toasted, ~{3-4%mins}.

> Watch it like a hawk as breadcrumbs can burn easily.

Meanwhile, boil a full #kettle{}.

Peel and grate the @garlic cloves{2} (or use a garlic press).

Once toasted, transfer the crumbs to a small #bowl{} and set aside.

Pour the boiled water into a large #saucepan{} with @salt{1/2%tsp} on high heat.

Add the @orzo{180%g} to the water and bring back to the boil. Cook until tender, ~{10%mins}.

Once cooked, drain in a #sieve{} and pop back in the pan. Drizzle with oil and stir through to stop it sticking together.

Meanwhile, wipe out the (now empty) frying pan and pop on medium heat (no oil).

Once hot, add the @diced chorizo{60%g} and fry until it starts to brown, ~{3-4%mins}.

For the final ~{1%min}, stir in the @Cajun spice mix{1%sachet} and cook until fragrant.

Add the garlic and @tomato puree{30%g} to the pan, then stir-fry for ~{1%min} more.

Stir the @creme fraiche{150%g}, @chicken stock paste{10%g}, @sugar{1%tsp} and @water for the sauce{75%ml} into the frying pan.

Bring to the boil, then reduce the heat and simmer until thickened, ~{3-4%mins}.

Once the sauce has thickened, stir in the @peas{120%g}, @grated hard Italian style cheese{20%g} and @butter{20%g}.

Heat until the peas are piping hot and the butter and cheese have melted, ~{1%min}.

Stir the cooked orzo into the sauce. Mix well to combine.

Taste and season with @salt{} and @pepper{} if needed. Add a splash of water if you feel it needs it.

Share the creamy Cajun chorizo orzo between your serving bowls.

Sprinkle over the crumb topping to finish. Enjoy!